  "opinion": "As a plumber in Rome with a background that’s not academic but hands-on, I’ve seen how science gets reduced to textbooks and exams for many. The gender gap in science isn’t just about women being underrepresented—it’s about how we teach it, how we value practical skills, and how we treat people who don’t fit the ‘smart’ mold. My own experience as a working-class man with a master’s-educated father and a primary-school-educated mother shows me that education isn’t the only path to understanding science. When I fix a leaky pipe, I’m not doing something ‘less scientific’ than a lab experiment; it’s a different kind of problem-solving. The gap isn’t about gender—it’s about who gets to be seen as competent in science. We need to stop making science feel like a competition for the ‘smartest’ and start valuing all kinds of knowledge. I’ve felt depressed lately, and I think the pressure to be a ‘scientist’ is too much for people who don’t have the same opportunities. We should address this by making science more accessible, not just through better education but by showing that real-world problem-solving counts too. In Rome, where the streets are full of people fixing things, I see that science isn’t just for the classroom—it’s in the hands of everyone who builds, repairs, and creates. Let’s stop pretending that only certain people can be scientists.",
